'''[[Homelessness]] in [[Switzerland]]''' is a known social issue, however, there are few estimates as to the number of Swiss people affected.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.homelessworldcup.org/homelessness-statistics/|title=Global Homelessness Statistics|publisher=Homeless World Cup}}</ref> Homelessness is less visible in Switzerland than in many other Western countries. The majority of homeless people in [[Geneva]] are Swiss or French, with a minority from other countries.<ref name=fallout>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/cities/2014/oct/22/new-cold-war-geneva-switzerland-fallout-bunkers-homeless-shelters|title=New cold war: the Geneva fallout bunkers doubling as homeless shelters|first=Kate|last=Bond|date=22 October 2014|publisher=|via=The Guardian}}</ref>

One Swiss study found that 1.6 percent of all patients admitted to psych wards were homeless. The study reported that social factors and psychopathology are independently contributing to the risk of homelessness.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Homelessness among people with severe mental illness in Switzerland|first1=Christoph|last1=Lauber|first2=Barbara|last2=Lay|first3=Wulf|last3=Rössler|date=22 January 2005|publisher=|journal=Swiss Med Wkly|volume=135|issue=3-4|pages=50–56|via=|pmid=15729607}}</ref>

In 2014, Swiss authorities reportedly began allowing homeless people to sleep in [[fallout shelter]]s built during the [[Cold War]].<ref name=fallout/>

There are a number of centers for providing food for the homeless, including the Suneboge community centre.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.swissinfo.ch/eng/society/poverty-in-switzerland_broke-and-homeless-on-the-streets-of-zurich/41058006|title=Broke and homeless on the streets of Zurich - SWI swissinfo.ch|first=Luigi Jorio,|last=swissinfo.ch|publisher=}}</ref>

