{{Infobox theatre|name=Kharkiv Ukrainian Drama Theatre|native_name=Харківський академічний український драматичний театр імені Тараса Шевченка|native_name_lang=uk|image=TeatrSzewczenki.jpg|image_size=274|image_alt=Kharkiv Ukrainian Drama Theatre|caption=Entrance to Kharkiv Drama Theatre|address=9 Sumska Street|city=[[Kharkiv]]|country=[[Ukraine]]|architect=|owner=|capacity=Main Stage: 900 Small Stage: 115|type=dramatic theatre|opened=1922 / 1935|reopened=|website={{URL|http://www.theatre-shevchenko.com.ua/|Theatre website}}}}

The '''Kharkiv Ukrainian Drama Theatre''' also known as the '''Taras Shevchenko Kharkiv Academic Ukrainian Drama Theatre''' is a [[List of national theatres|national theater]]<ref name=":0" /> founded in 1935 out of remnants of the suppressed Berezil Theater, which was founded by [[Les Kurbas]] in 1922.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://www.encyclopediaofukraine.com/display.asp?linkpath=pages%5CK%5CH%5CKharkivUkrainianDramaTheater.htm|title=Kharkiv Ukrainian Drama Theater|website=www.encyclopediaofukraine.com|access-date=2017-01-12}}</ref> Kharkiv Ukrainian Drama Theatre has two stages: Main Stage (900 seats) and Small Stage "Berezil" (115 seats).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theatre-shevchenko.com.ua/about/shema.php|title=Харківський Державний Академічний Драматичний Театр ім. Т.Г.Шевченка|website=www.theatre-shevchenko.com.ua|access-date=2017-01-12}}</ref>

The theater's repertoire was formed by directors trained in [[Konstantin Stanislavski|Konstantin Stanislavsky]]'s school, and since 1990s by directors trained by [[Anatoly Vasiliev]]. Over the years the theater's ensemble included many renowned artists such as [[Vadym Meller]] (stage designer), [[Leonid Bykov]] (actor), [[Amvrosy Buchma]] (actor, star of film ''[[Ivan the Terrible (1944 film)|Ivan the Terrible]]),'' [[Andriy Zholdak]] (theatre director), [[Andrzej Szczytko]] (theatre director).<ref name=":0" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://eepap.culture.pl/event/antigone-new-york-ivan-franko-national-theatre-kiev|title="Antigone in New York" in Ivan Franko National Theatre, Kiev|newspaper=eepap.culture.pl|access-date=2017-01-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://eepap.culture.pl/person/andrzej-szczytko|title=Andrzej Szczytko|newspaper=eepap.culture.pl|access-date=2017-01-12}}</ref>

From 2002 to 2005,  [[Andriy Zholdak]] was the [[artistic director]] of the theater, where he produced five plays, which, apart from Ukraine, were also presented in many European countries including Germany, France, Finland, Netherlands, Poland, Austria, Romania and Russia, at well known festivals. In 2005, after Kharkiv authorities prohibited his staging of ''[[Romeo and Juliet|Romeo and Juliet. A Fragment]]'' Zholdak was forced to leave the theater.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://svobodazholdaktheatre.com/en/director|title=DIRECTOR / Svoboda Zholdak Theatre|website=svobodazholdaktheatre.com|access-date=2017-01-12}}</ref>

In 2004, the theater's [[ensemble cast|ensemble]] was named by [[UNESCO]] critics as one of the best ensembles in Europe.

